\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$K$\end{document} no longer need to be an integer or a divisor of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$n$\end{document}, and the entire range \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$K\in (1,\infty )$\end{document} is available, although in practice values in the range 5–10 may be advisable.

We recommend performing the simulations at least 1000 times, in order to minimize stochastic variation. Each simulation step of the independent projack corresponds to a single random \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$K$\end{document}-fold split of the projack, and so the independent projack is somewhat faster and uses much less memory (handling vectors rather than matrices).

